<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1437,1286,1637]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1286,1312]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[281,435,1287,1313]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Faltala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcipennis">
<emphasis box="[281,435,1287,1313]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">F. furcipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zahniser" authorityYear="2021" box="[931,1013,1287,1313]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Faltala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[931,1013,1287,1313]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Faltala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the male pygofer ventral lobe extending well beyond dorsal half of pygofer and not terminating in a claw-like spine, subgenital plate lateral margin sinuate and tapering to rounded apex, style apophysis incrassate and club-like, aedeagus branched and vaguely Tshaped in lateral view, and aedeagal shaft relatively thick and arising dorsally from base of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
